
**********************************************************************************
This work is the outcome of a three-months internship at the Aalto University Data Communication Software lab. The ultimate purpose of this ongoing research is the optimization of the WiFi interface operation resulting in battery energy savings.
********************************************************************************** 


Before you move on make sure :

1) You have the Android SDK installed on your machine (suggestion: use the Android SDK in conjunction with Eclipse and Android Developer Tools)

http://developer.android.com/sdk/index.html
http://developer.android.com/tools/help/adt.html


2) You have read and understood the use of Android Debug Bridge (adb)

http://developer.android.com/tools/help/adb.html


3) You have rooted you handset

http://nexusshacks.com/nexus-s-root/how-to-root-nexus-s-or-nexus-s-4g-on-ics-or-gingerbread/   (for Nexus S obviously)


4) You have installed busybox on your handset. 

http://www.busybox.net/
https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.jrummy.busybox.installer&hl=en


5) You have understood how the Android Open Source Project(AOSP) is set up.

 http://source.android.com/source/initializing.html


6) You have understood what the Native Development Kit (NDK) is and how you can use it to build native code for Android.

 http://developer.android.com/tools/sdk/ndk/index.html





More details of this project setup and instructions on how to run the software are available on each subdirectory README.
